# TableOfContents (React Router, `.tsx`)

## Purpose
Auto-collapsing article table of contents for React Router routes. It accepts h2/h3 TOC data, strips emoji from labels, keeps h3s available for active-section tracking, but renders only primary h2 anchors. Uses Tailwind indigo link styling.

## Props

### Required
| Prop | Type | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `items` | `TocItem[]` | Array of TOC items with labels and anchors |

### Optional
| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|---|---|---|---|
| `title` | `string` | `'Contents'` | TOC section title |
| `ariaLabel` | `string` | `'Table of contents'` | Accessible label |
| `className` | `string` | - | Additional CSS classes |
| `activeId` | `string` | - | Currently active section ID. If omitted, the component tracks it with `IntersectionObserver`. |
| `onItemClick` | `(id: string) => void` | - | Callback when item clicked |

## Types
```ts
export interface TocItem {
    id: string;
    label: string;
    level: 2 | 3;
    children?: TocItem[];
}
```

## Semantic Hints
`toc`, `table-of-contents`, `navigation`, `outline`, `contents`, `nav`, `page-nav`, `section-nav`, `sidebar-toc`

## When to Use
Use in article route modules, typically where `ArticleEnhancer` injects content into an `ArticleTocPlaceholder`. Do not use React Router `<Link>` for same-page anchors; use native `<a href="#id">`.

## Structure
```tsx
<aside>
    <h2>Contents</h2>
    <nav aria-label="Table of contents">
        <ul>
            <li>
                <a href="#section-id" aria-current="true">Section Label</a>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </nav>
</aside>
```

## Complete Component Example

